article.headline: Gophers leave quite an impression on Michigan's coach
article.linkText: It's an impressive Big Ten start for No. 10 Minnesota
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A soft nonconference schedule sure didn't
have an effect on Minnesota's first crack at Big Ten competition.

	   Lindsay Whalen scored 30 points on 10-for-13 shooting and Corrin
Von Wald had 13 of her 18 points in the first half to lead the
10th-ranked Golden Gophers to a 98-70 victory Thursday night over
Michigan.

	   Minnesota hasn't played a Top 25 team yet and won its first 11
games by an average of 23 points, but as Pam
Borton, in her first year as the Minnesota coach, pointed out, eight of those were on the road.

	   ''Everybody was talking about how weak our nonconference
schedule was,'' Borton said. ''It was weak, but we've been through
a lot. We haven't been in Williams Arena for a week. It was nice to
be home.''

	   Stephanie Gandy had 23 points on 10-for-12 shooting for the
Wolverines (9-3, 0-1), who've lost two of three. Michigan's opponents have
a combined winning percentage above .600.

	   The Golden Gophers (12-0, 1-0 Big Ten), sporting the highest
ranking in the program's 29-year history, won their conference
opener for just the second time in nine seasons.

	   Minnesota, which tied Penn State for second place in the Big Ten
last year, began the conference schedule last season with a home
defeat against the Nittany Lions.

	   ''More than anything, it was nice to get the Big Ten off to a
big start,'' Whalen said.

	   This was Minnesota's first test, one Wolverines coach Sue
Guevara said she believes the Gophers easily passed.

	   ''I watched four tapes of Minnesota and in those four tapes, I
didn't quite see the team I saw today,'' Guevara said. ''That team
was on all cylinders for 40 minutes. We just got an old-fashioned
butt-whipping.''

	   Minnesota, which began the week third in the nation in scoring,
showed it could play a little defense, too. Tabitha Pool,
Michigan's second-leading scorer, was held to four points -- more
than 10 below her average.

	   The Gophers also owned a 37-27 rebounding edge and got nearly
everyone who stepped on the court involved.

	   ''It's not just a Whalen show,'' Guevara said. ''I'm very
impressed, unfortunately.''

	   Minnesota faces an even bigger challenge on Monday at Penn State.

	   ''You know what I'm really impressed with?'' Guevara said.
''Their defense. Last year, it was all zone. But those kids have
really bought into Pam's system.''

	   Michigan closed to seven following a first-half basket by
Gandy, but the Gophers scored 10 consecutive points -- including four
by Whalen and a shot clock-beating 3-pointer by Tanisha Gilbert -- and charged to a 43-26 lead just before halftime.

	   Minnesota used a 6-0 run over 41 seconds of the early stage of
second half to increase its lead to 51-32. The Gophers led by as
many as 34 on a pair of foul shots by Kim Prince that made it 77-43
with 10:09 left.

	   McCarville had 13 of her 16 points in the second half, and
Kadidja Andersson had a career-best eight assists for Minnesota.

	   Whalen, the Big Ten Player of the Year, sped past Gandy and made
a nifty behind-the-back pass to Janel McCarville that netted an easy
layup with 6:29 to go that made it 86-54. The up-and-down pace at
which Minnesota played seemed to wear out the Wolverines, who start
two freshmen and a sophomore.

	   ''Our best offense isn't necessarily setting up in the
half-court,'' Whalen said.
